Veins+INET tutorial example.

This simulation requires sumo-launchd to be started and listening for
connections on a TCP socket, e.g. using "~/src/veins/sumo-launchd.py -vv".

Available scenario families:
- square (default): `plain`, `edca_only`, `edca_v2x`
- highway corridor: `highway_plain`, `highway_edca_only`, `highway_edca_v2x`

Legacy compatibility aliases are also available:
- square: `veins_edca`, `veins_edca_with_cw`
- highway: `highway_veins_edca`, `highway_veins_edca_with_cw`

References used for highway realism:
- SUMO vehicle types, flows, and route definitions:
  https://sumo.dlr.de/docs/Definition_of_Vehicles,_Vehicle_Types,_and_Routes.html
- SUMO Enhanced IDM (EIDM):
  https://sumo.dlr.de/docs/Car-Following-Models/EIDM.html
- SUMO lane-changing model paper (LC2013 context):
  https://elib.dlr.de/102254/
- SUMO route calibration (`routeSampler.py`):
  https://sumo.dlr.de/docs/Tools/Turns.html#routesampler-py
- SUMO calibrator:
  https://sumo.dlr.de/docs/Simulation/Calibrator.html
- INET path-loss model comparison (including `TwoRayInterference`):
  https://inet.omnetpp.org/docs/showcases/wireless/pathloss/doc/index.html
